TITLE: Using Technical Indicators with QuantBook
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to create and visualize a Bollinger Bands indicator for SPY. The example demonstrates creating the indicator, retrieving historical data, formatting the output, and plotting the results.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Research/BasicQuantBookTemplate.ipynb#2025-04-21_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
# Example with BB, it is a datapoint indicator
# Define the indicator
bb = BollingerBands(30, 2)

# Gets historical data of indicator
bbdf = qb.Indicator(bb, "SPY", 360, Resolution.Daily).data_frame

# drop undesired fields
bbdf = bbdf.drop('standarddeviation', 1)

# Plot
bbdf.plot()
```

TITLE: Creating and Plotting SMA Crossover for EURUSD
DESCRIPTION: Implements a Moving Average crossover strategy using 50-day (fast) and 200-day (slow) Simple Moving Averages on EURUSD. Shows combining multiple indicators for analysis.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Research/KitchenSinkQuantBookTemplate.ipynb#2025-04-21_snippet_23

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
# SMA cross:
symbol = "EURUSD"
# Get History 
hist = qb.History([symbol], 500, Resolution.Daily)
# Get the fast moving average
fast = qb.Indicator(SimpleMovingAverage(50), symbol, 500, Resolution.Daily)
# Get the fast moving average
slow = qb.Indicator(SimpleMovingAverage(200), symbol, 500, Resolution.Daily)

# Remove undesired columns and rename others 
fast = fast.drop('rollingsum', 1).rename(columns={'simplemovingaverage': 'fast'})
slow = slow.drop('rollingsum', 1).rename(columns={'simplemovingaverage': 'slow'})

# Concatenate the information and plot 
df = pd.concat([hist.loc[symbol]["close"], fast, slow], axis=1).dropna(axis=0)
df.plot()
```

TITLE: Retrieving Custom Data History in C# using QuantBook
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to use QuantBook to add custom data and retrieve historical data. It creates a QuantBook instance, adds custom data, and fetches historical data for a specified time range.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/Research/RegressionTemplates/BasicTemplateCustomDataTypeHistoryResearchCSharp.ipynb#2025-04-21_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: csharp
CODE:
```
var qb = new QuantBook();
var symbol = qb.AddData<CustomDataType>("CustomDataType", Resolution.Hour).Symbol;

var start = new DateTime(2017, 8, 20);
var end = start.AddHours(48);
var history = qb.History<CustomDataType>(symbol, start, end, Resolution.Hour).ToList();

if (history.Count == 0)
{
    throw new Exception("No history data returned");
}
```

TITLE: Defining IPositionGroupBuyingPowerModel Interface in C#
DESCRIPTION: Interface definition for IPositionGroupBuyingPowerModel which provides methods for margin calculations, buying power checks, and order quantity determinations for position groups. It includes specialized functionality like GetReservedBuyingPowerImpact for 'what-if' analysis on how trades might impact existing position groups.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Common/Securities/Positions/readme.md#2025-04-21_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: csharp
CODE:
```
// See: https://github.com/QuantConnect/Lean/blob/refactor-4065-position-groups/Common/Securities/Positions/IPositionGroupBuyingPowerModel.cs

/// <summary>
/// Gets the margin currently allocated to the specified holding
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the security</param>
/// <returns>The maintenance margin required for the </returns>
MaintenanceMargin GetMaintenanceMargin(PositionGroupMaintenanceMarginParameters parameters);

/// <summary>
/// The margin that must be held in order to increase the position by the provided quantity
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the security and quantity</param>
InitialMargin GetInitialMarginRequirement(PositionGroupInitialMarginParameters parameters);

/// <summary>
/// Gets the total margin required to execute the specified order in units of the account currency including fees
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the portfolio, the security and the order</param>
/// <returns>The total margin in terms of the currency quoted in the order</returns>
InitialMargin GetInitialMarginRequiredForOrder(PositionGroupInitialMarginForOrderParameters parameters);

/// <summary>
/// Computes the impact on the portfolio's buying power from adding the position group to the portfolio. This is
/// a 'what if' analysis to determine what the state of the portfolio would be if these changes were applied. The
/// delta (before - after) is the margin requirement for adding the positions and if the margin used after the changes
/// are applied is less than the total portfolio value, this indicates sufficient capital.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the portfolio and a position group containing the contemplated
/// changes to the portfolio</param>
/// <returns>Returns the portfolio's total portfolio value and margin used before and after the position changes are applied</returns>
ReservedBuyingPowerImpact GetReservedBuyingPowerImpact(
    ReservedBuyingPowerImpactParameters parameters
    );

/// <summary>
/// Check if there is sufficient buying power for the position group to execute this order.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the portfolio, the position group and the order</param>
/// <returns>Returns buying power information for an order against a position group</returns>
HasSufficientBuyingPowerForOrderResult HasSufficientBuyingPowerForOrder(
    HasSufficientPositionGroupBuyingPowerForOrderParameters parameters
    );

/// <summary>
/// Computes the amount of buying power reserved by the provided position group
/// </summary>
ReservedBuyingPowerForPositionGroup GetReservedBuyingPowerForPositionGroup(
    ReservedBuyingPowerForPositionGroupParameters parameters
    );

/// <summary>
/// Get the maximum position group order quantity to obtain a position with a given buying power
/// percentage. Will not take into account free buying power.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the portfolio, the position group and the target
///     signed buying power percentage</param>
/// <returns>Returns the maximum allowed market order quantity and if zero, also the reason</returns>
GetMaximumLotsResult GetMaximumLotsForTargetBuyingPower(
    GetMaximumLotsForTargetBuyingPowerParameters parameters
    );

/// <summary>
/// Get the maximum market position group order quantity to obtain a delta in the buying power used by a position group.
/// The deltas sign defines the position side to apply it to, positive long, negative short.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the portfolio, the position group and the delta buying power</param>
/// <returns>Returns the maximum allowed market order quantity and if zero, also the reason</returns>
/// <remarks>Used by the margin call model to reduce the position by a delta percent.</remarks>
GetMaximumLotsResult GetMaximumLotsForDeltaBuyingPower(
    GetMaximumLotsForDeltaBuyingPowerParameters parameters
    );

/// <summary>
/// Gets the buying power available for a position group trade
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">A parameters object containing the algorithm's portfolio, security, and order direction</param>
/// <returns>The buying power available for the trade</returns>
PositionGroupBuyingPower GetPositionGroupBuyingPower(PositionGroupBuyingPowerParameters parameters);
```

TITLE: Defining Custom Data Type in C# for QuantConnect LEAN
DESCRIPTION: This snippet defines a CustomDataType class that inherits from DynamicData. It includes properties for OHLC data and implements methods for retrieving data source and parsing CSV data.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/Research/RegressionTemplates/BasicTemplateCustomDataTypeHistoryResearchCSharp.ipynb#2025-04-21_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: csharp
CODE:
```
class CustomDataType : DynamicData
{
    public decimal Open;
    public decimal High;
    public decimal Low;
    public decimal Close;

    public override SubscriptionDataSource GetSource(SubscriptionDataConfig config, DateTime date, bool isLiveMode)
    {
        var source = "https://www.dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/d83xvd7mm9fzpk0/path_to_my_csv_data.csv?dl=0";
        return new SubscriptionDataSource(source, SubscriptionTransportMedium.RemoteFile);
    }

    public override BaseData Reader(SubscriptionDataConfig config, string line, DateTime date, bool isLiveMode)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(line.Trim()))
        {
            return null;
        }

        try
        {
            var csv = line.Split(",");
            var data = new CustomDataType()
            {
                Symbol = config.Symbol,
                Time = DateTime.ParseExact(csv[0], DateFormat.DB, CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).AddHours(20),
                Value = csv[4].ToDecimal(),
                Open = csv[1].ToDecimal(),
                High = csv[2].ToDecimal(),
                Low = csv[3].ToDecimal(),
                Close = csv[4].ToDecimal()
            };

            return data;
        }
        catch
        {
            return null;
        }
    }
}
```

TITLE: Implementing Custom Financial Data Type
DESCRIPTION: Defines a custom data type class that inherits from PythonData to handle financial data from a CSV source. Implements methods for data source configuration and parsing of OHLC (Open, High, Low, Close) price data.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/Research/RegressionTemplates/BasicTemplateCustomDataTypeHistoryResearchPython.ipynb#2025-04-21_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
class CustomDataType(PythonData):

    def GetSource(self, config: SubscriptionDataConfig, date: datetime, isLive: bool) -> SubscriptionDataSource:
        source = "https://www.dl.dropboxusercontent.com/s/d83xvd7mm9fzpk0/path_to_my_csv_data.csv?dl=0"
        return SubscriptionDataSource(source, SubscriptionTransportMedium.RemoteFile)

    def Reader(self, config: SubscriptionDataConfig, line: str, date: datetime, isLive: bool) -> BaseData:
        if not (line.strip()):
            return None

        data = line.split(',')
        obj_data = CustomDataType()
        obj_data.Symbol = config.Symbol

        try:
            obj_data.Time = datetime.strptime(data[0], '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S') + timedelta(hours=20)
            obj_data["open"] = float(data[1])
            obj_data["high"] = float(data[2])
            obj_data["low"] = float(data[3])
            obj_data["close"] = float(data[4])
            obj_data.Value = obj_data["close"]

            # property for asserting the correct data is fetched
            obj_data["some_property"] = "some property value"
        except ValueError:
            return None

        return obj_data

    def __str__ (self):
        return f"Time: {self.Time}, Value: {self.Value}, SomeProperty: {self['some_property']}, Open: {self['open']}, High: {self['high']}, Low: {self['low']}, Close: {self['close']}"
```

TITLE: Implementing GetMaximumLotsForTargetBuyingPower for Position Groups in C#
DESCRIPTION: This C# code snippet implements the `GetMaximumLotsForTargetBuyingPower` method. This method calculates the maximum order quantity to achieve a target buying power percentage. It delegates to the security's `BuyingPowerModel` to get the maximum order quantity and converts the result from number of lots to a quantity using the security's lot size.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Common/Securities/Positions/readme.md#2025-04-21_snippet_9

LANGUAGE: csharp
CODE:
```
/// <summary>
/// Get the maximum position group order quantity to obtain a position with a given buying power
/// percentage. Will not take into account free buying power.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the portfolio, the position group and the target
///     signed buying power percentage</param>
/// <returns>Returns the maximum allowed market order quantity and if zero, also the reason</returns>
public override GetMaximumLotsResult GetMaximumLotsForTargetBuyingPower(
    GetMaximumLotsForTargetBuyingPowerParameters parameters
    )
{
    // simply delegates to security.BuyingPowerModel.GetMaximumOrderQuantityForTargetBuyingPower
    // and then converts the result which is in number of lots into a quantity using the lot size
    var quantity = result.Quantity / security.SymbolProperties.LotSize;
}
```

TITLE: Defining IPositionGroupResolver Interface in C#
DESCRIPTION: The IPositionGroupResolver interface defines methods for grouping positions, resolving position groups, and determining impacted groups for what-if analysis. This interface enables efficient margin requirement calculations by organizing security holdings into optimized groups.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Common/Securities/Positions/readme.md#2025-04-21_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: csharp
CODE:
```
/// <summary>
/// Attempts to group the specified positions into a new <see cref="IPositionGroup"/> using an
/// appropriate <see cref="IPositionGroupBuyingPowerModel"/> for position groups created via this
/// resolver.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="positions">The positions to be grouped</param>
/// <param name="group">The grouped positions when this resolver is able to, otherwise null</param>
/// <returns>True if this resolver can group the specified positions, otherwise false</returns>
bool TryGroup(IReadOnlyCollection<IPosition> positions, out IPositionGroup group);

/// <summary>
/// Resolves the position groups that exist within the specified collection of positions.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="positions">The collection of positions</param>
/// <returns>An enumerable of position groups</returns>
PositionGroupCollection Resolve(PositionCollection positions);

/// <summary>
/// Determines the position groups that would be evaluated for grouping of the specified
/// positions were passed into the <see cref="Resolve"/> method.
/// </summary>
/// <remarks>
/// This function allows us to determine a set of impacted groups and run the resolver on just
/// those groups in order to support what-if analysis
/// </remarks>
/// <param name="groups">The existing position groups</param>
/// <param name="positions">The positions being changed</param>
/// <returns>An enumerable containing the position groups that could be impacted by the specified position changes</returns>
IEnumerable<IPositionGroup> GetImpactedGroups(
    PositionGroupCollection groups,
    IReadOnlyCollection<IPosition> positions
    );
```

TITLE: Defining IPosition Interface in C#
DESCRIPTION: The IPosition interface defines the core properties of a position including Symbol, Quantity, and UnitQuantity. UnitQuantity represents the smallest allowable quantity increment according to the group definition.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Common/Securities/Positions/readme.md#2025-04-21_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: csharp
CODE:
```
/// <summary>
/// The symbol
/// </summary>
Symbol Symbol { get; }

/// <summary>
/// The quantity
/// </summary>
decimal Quantity { get; }

/// <summary>
/// The unit quantity. The unit quantities of a group define the group. For example, a covered
/// call has 100 units of stock and -1 units of call contracts.
/// </summary>
decimal UnitQuantity { get; }
```

TITLE: Implementing GetMaximumLotsForDeltaBuyingPower for Position Groups in C#
DESCRIPTION: This C# code snippet shows how to implement the `GetMaximumLotsForDeltaBuyingPower` method. It determines the maximum market order quantity to achieve a delta in buying power. It delegates to the security's `BuyingPowerModel` and converts the maximum quantity into number of lots, using the security's lot size.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Common/Securities/Positions/readme.md#2025-04-21_snippet_10

LANGUAGE: csharp
CODE:
```
/// <summary>
/// Get the maximum market position group order quantity to obtain a delta in the buying power used by a position group.
/// The deltas sign defines the position side to apply it to, positive long, negative short.
/// </summary>
/// <param name="parameters">An object containing the portfolio, the position group and the delta buying power</param>
/// <returns>Returns the maximum allowed market order quantity and if zero, also the reason</returns>
/// <remarks>Used by the margin call model to reduce the position by a delta percent.</remarks>
public override GetMaximumLotsResult GetMaximumLotsForDeltaBuyingPower(
    GetMaximumLotsForDeltaBuyingPowerParameters parameters
    )
{
    // simply delegates to security.BuyingPowerModel.GetMaximumOrderQuantityForDeltaBuyingPower
    // and converts the maximum quantity into number of lots using the security's lot size
}
```

TITLE: Parsing SPY Stock Price Data CSV in Python
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet demonstrates how to parse the SPY stock price data CSV file using Python's csv module. It reads the file, processes each row, and creates a list of dictionaries containing the stock price information.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/spy_rocr.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
import csv
from datetime import datetime

def parse_spy_data(file_path):
    spy_data = []
    with open(file_path, 'r') as csvfile:
        reader = csv.reader(csvfile)
        for row in reader:
            date = datetime.strptime(row[0], '%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p')
            spy_data.append({
                'date': date,
                'open': float(row[1]),
                'high': float(row[2]),
                'low': float(row[3]),
                'close': float(row[4]),
                'volume': int(row[5]),
                'additional_value': float(row[6])
            })
    return spy_data

# Usage
file_path = 'path/to/spy_data.csv'
spy_stock_data = parse_spy_data(file_path)
```

TITLE: Parsing EURUSD Forex Data CSV in Python
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet demonstrates how to parse the EURUSD forex data CSV file using Python. It reads the file, converts the timestamp to a datetime object, and creates a list of dictionaries containing the parsed data.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/eurusd60_dem.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
import csv
from datetime import datetime

def parse_eurusd_data(file_path):
    data = []
    with open(file_path, 'r') as csvfile:
        reader = csv.reader(csvfile)
        for row in reader:
            timestamp = datetime.strptime(row[1], '%Y/%m/%d %H:%M:%S')
            data.append({
                'index': int(row[0]),
                'timestamp': timestamp,
                'open': float(row[2]),
                'high': float(row[3]),
                'low': float(row[4]),
                'close': float(row[5]),
                'volume': int(row[6]),
                'metric': float(row[7])
            })
    return data

# Usage
file_path = 'eurusd_data.csv'
parsed_data = parse_eurusd_data(file_path)
print(parsed_data[0])  # Print the first parsed row
```

TITLE: Parsing CSV Stock Data in Python
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet demonstrates how to parse the CSV data using Python's csv module. It reads the file, extracts the date and closing price, and stores them in a dictionary.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/spy_with_adx.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
import csv
from datetime import datetime

stock_data = {}

with open('stock_data.csv', 'r') as file:
    csv_reader = csv.reader(file)
    for row in csv_reader:
        date = datetime.strptime(row[0], '%m/%d/%Y')
        closing_price = float(row[4])
        stock_data[date] = closing_price

print(stock_data)
```

TITLE: Calculating Daily Returns in R
DESCRIPTION: This R code snippet shows how to calculate daily returns for each stock using the closing prices. It assumes the data has been loaded into a data frame called 'stock_data'.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/arms_data.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: r
CODE:
```
library(dplyr)

# Assuming 'stock_data' is a data frame with the CSV data
stock_data <- stock_data %>%
  group_by(symbol) %>%
  arrange(date) %>%
  mutate(daily_return = (close - lag(close)) / lag(close)) %>%
  ungroup()

# View results
head(stock_data)
```

TITLE: Parsing CSV Stock Data in Python
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet demonstrates how to parse the CSV stock data using Python. It assumes the data is stored in a file named 'stock_data.csv'.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/spy_mass_index_25.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
import csv
from datetime import datetime

with open('stock_data.csv', 'r') as file:
    csv_reader = csv.reader(file)
    for row in csv_reader:
        date = datetime.strptime(row[0], '%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p')
        open_price = float(row[1])
        high = float(row[2])
        low = float(row[3])
        close = float(row[4])
        volume = float(row[5])
        
        # Process the data as needed
        print(f"Date: {date}, Close: {close}, Volume: {volume}")
```

TITLE: Calculating Moving Averages in Python
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet shows how to calculate a simple moving average using the closing prices from the CSV data. It uses pandas to read the CSV and compute a 5-day moving average.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/spy_with_adx.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_csv('stock_data.csv', parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')
df['5_day_ma'] = df['Close'].rolling(window=5).mean()

print(df[['Close', '5_day_ma']])
```

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
import csv

def parse_stock_data(file_path):
    stock_data = []
    with open(file_path, 'r') as csvfile:
        reader = csv.DictReader(csvfile, fieldnames=['date', 'symbol', 'open', 'high', 'low', 'close', 'volume', 'field1', 'field2', 'field3', 'field4'])
        for row in reader:
            stock_data.append(row)
    return stock_data

# Usage
file_path = 'path/to/stock_data.csv'
data = parse_stock_data(file_path)

# Access specific data
print(data[0]['symbol'], data[0]['close'])
```

TITLE: Parsing CSV Stock Price Data in Python
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet demonstrates how to parse the CSV data structure present in the file. It assumes the data is loaded into a string variable 'data' and uses the csv module to process each row.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/spy_stc.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
import csv
import datetime

data = """1233585000,81.57001,87.74001,73.81,73.92999,0.001525878906
1236004200,72.52,83.3,67.10001,79.52,0.0007629394531
# ... more data ..."""

rows = csv.reader(data.split('\n'))
for row in rows:
    timestamp = datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(int(row[0]))
    open_price = float(row[1])
    high_price = float(row[2])
    low_price = float(row[3])
    close_price = float(row[4])
    volume = float(row[5])
    
    print(f"Date: {timestamp}, Open: {open_price}, Close: {close_price}, Volume: {volume}")
```

TITLE: Parsing CSV Stock Data in Python
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet demonstrates how to parse the CSV stock data using Python. It splits each line into its components and creates a structured representation of the stock information.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/spy_t3.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: Python
CODE:
```
import csv
from datetime import datetime

class StockData:
    def __init__(self, date, open, high, low, close, volume, adj_close):
        self.date = datetime.strptime(date, '%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p')
        self.open = float(open)
        self.high = float(high)
        self.low = float(low)
        self.close = float(close)
        self.volume = int(volume)
        self.adj_close = float(adj_close)

stock_data = []
with open('stock_data.csv', 'r') as file:
    csv_reader = csv.reader(file)
    for row in csv_reader:
        stock_data.append(StockData(*row))

# Example usage
print(f"Date: {stock_data[0].date}, Close: {stock_data[0].close}")
```

TITLE: Parsing CSV Stock Data in Python
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet demonstrates how to parse the CSV stock data using Python. It reads the file, processes each line, and extracts relevant information such as date, opening price, closing price, and volume.
SOURCE: https://github.com/quantconnect/lean/blob/master/Tests/TestData/spy_min.txt#2025-04-21_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: python
CODE:
```
import csv
from datetime import datetime

with open('stock_data.csv', 'r') as file:
    csv_reader = csv.reader(file)
    for row in csv_reader:
        date = datetime.strptime(row[0], '%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p')
        open_price = float(row[1])
        high_price = float(row[2])
        low_price = float(row[3])
        close_price = float(row[4])
```
